vivid examples, and interesting problems, Stillwell demonstrates that elementary mathematics becomes advanced with the intervention of infinity. Infinity has been observed throughout mathematical history, but the recent development of "reverse mathematics" confirms that infinity is essential for proving well-known theorems, and helps to determine the nature, contours, and borders of elementary mathematics.Elements of Mathematics gives readers, from high school students to professional mathematicians, the highlights of elementary mathematics and glimpses of the parts of math beyond its boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMathematicsxStudy and teaching (Higher). 7aMATHEMATICS / History & Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAbstract algebra.  aAddition.  aAlgebra.  aAlgebraic equation.  aAlgebraic number.  aAlgorithm.  aArbitrarily large.  aArithmetic.  aAxiom.  aBinomial coefficient.  aBolzano–Weierstrass theorem.  aCalculation.  aCantor's diagonal argument.  aChurch–Turing thesis.  aClosure (mathematics).  aCoefficient.  aCombination.  aCombinatorics.  aCommutative property.  aComplex number.  aComputable number.  aComputation.  aConstructible number.  aContinuous function (set theory).  aContinuous function.  aContinuum hypothesis.  aDedekind cut.  aDirichlet's approximation theorem.  aDivisibility rule.  aElementary function.  aElementary mathematics.  aEquation.  aEuclidean division.  aEuclidean geometry.  aExponentiation.  aExtended Euclidean algorithm.  aFactorization.  aFibonacci number.  aFloor and ceiling functions.  aFundamental theorem of algebra.  aFundamental theorem.  aGaussian integer.  aGeometric series.  aGeometry.  aGödel's incompleteness theorems.  aHalting problem.  aInfimum and supremum.  aInteger factorizati